    {
      "id": "9fab7d2b69b261b9884e7bfeabed9134603bcf79",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 443,
        "name": "Andrew Perepechko",
        "email": "andrew.perepechko@hpe.com",
        "username": "panda"
      },
      "date": "2015-04-14 07:51:39.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2:\n\nIsn't it more straightforward to add tgt_sec_ctx_handlers to ofd_common_slice?\n\nLike in 0001-SNT-148-unsorted-fixes.patch attached to LU-6020.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "92bc274f33f8aee255fb7b858457cd50db5a0019",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 160,
        "name": "Sebastien Buisson",
        "email": "sebastien.buisson@bull.net",
        "username": "sebastien.buisson",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2015-04-15 15:01:14.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2:\n\n> I think it would be useful to see the commit message a little more\n > detailed as to why rather then explaining what the patch does. \n > From what I can see there is no return that is non-zero from\n > tgt_handle_request0 but there can be some assertions or LBUGs. \n > Were you hitting one of these?\n\nThe issue this patch addresses is that if SEC_CTX_* requests are processed normally, the server part fails to send a valid reply, so the client part never succeeds in initiating a security context. And then the client part keeps sending context initialization requests.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "40df859c6b02a0b87022de04c506bb004277c1d7",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 160,
        "name": "Sebastien Buisson",
        "email": "sebastien.buisson@bull.net",
        "username": "sebastien.buisson",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2015-04-15 15:10:06.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2:\n\n> Isn't it more straightforward to add tgt_sec_ctx_handlers to\n > ofd_common_slice?\n > \n > Like in 0001-SNT-148-unsorted-fixes.patch attached to LU-6020.\n\nI do not know, what would be the effect to add tgt_sec_ctx_handlers to ofd_common_slice? Would it make server part directly send reply when handling security context initialization requests?",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "41a904f2c75f089feac52439cdfd8638674c2801",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 443,
        "name": "Andrew Perepechko",
        "email": "andrew.perepechko@hpe.com",
        "username": "panda"
      },
      "date": "2015-04-15 15:27:51.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2:\n\n>  I do not know, what would be the effect to add tgt_sec_ctx_handlers to ofd_common_slice? Would it make server part directly send reply when handling security context initialization requests?\n\nAs far as I can see, it will do exactly the same as your patch, but without exposing particular operation  handling directly to tgt_handle_request0(). I guess tgt_sec_ctx_handlers was introduced specifically for this purpose.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "0c3041680607431124e57ec02e0559b29723b2a0",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 160,
        "name": "Sebastien Buisson",
        "email": "sebastien.buisson@bull.net",
        "username": "sebastien.buisson",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2015-04-15 15:30:12.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2:\n\n> >  I do not know, what would be the effect to add tgt_sec_ctx_handlers\n > to ofd_common_slice? Would it make server part directly send reply\n > when handling security context initialization requests?\n > \n > As far as I can see, it will do exactly the same as your patch, but\n > without exposing particular operation  handling directly to\n > tgt_handle_request0(). I guess tgt_sec_ctx_handlers was introduced\n > specifically for this purpose.\n\nOK then I will give it a try next week, and update the patch accordingly.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "a1322885d2e099b25a42622f644c48145c7cf192",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 160,
        "name": "Sebastien Buisson",
        "email": "sebastien.buisson@bull.net",
        "username": "sebastien.buisson",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2015-05-21 12:03:55.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2:\n\n> > As far as I can see, it will do exactly the same as your patch, but\n > > without exposing particular operation  handling directly to\n > > tgt_handle_request0(). I guess tgt_sec_ctx_handlers was introduced\n > > specifically for this purpose.\n > \n > OK then I will give it a try next week, and update the patch\n > accordingly.\n\nI tried to add tgt_sec_ctx_handlers to ofd_common_slice like in\n0001-SNT-148-unsorted-fixes.patch attached to LU-6020, but I did\nnot manage to make it work.\nThe problem is that when dealing with requests with opc == SEC_CTX_INIT,\nthere is no export associated yet, because these requests are sent\nbefore *_CONNECT requests (so req->rq_export is NULL).\nAs a consequence, we have no reference to the target, and thus we\nare not able to retrieve handlers from slice.\nI also tried to retrieve the target information by other means\nthan the export, but I was unsuccessful due to the fact that the\nSEC_CTX request format does not contain the target uuid.\n\nUnless there is another way to retrieve request handler, I would\ntend to stick with my initial proposal.\nWhat do you think?",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "76c6fcd2d88915d405736d188ef5bc459abf6419",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 525
      },
      "date": "2015-05-29 20:31:36.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2:\n\nI can't really think of any cleaner way to do it.  Can you put a comment in the code and maybe the commit message to summarize that SEC_CTX and SEC_CTX_INIT are called before rq_export is established so the normal *_common_slice handlers won't be called.  Then I'll +1 it.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
